::object_creation_01::Which statement best defines object creation in Java? {
=Object creation in Java is the process of allocating and initializing class instances.
~Variable semantics describe what a Java variable represents and how it behaves when assigned or passed.
~Types in Java classify values and determine valid operations at compile time.
~The new keyword allocates an object and invokes its constructor.
}

::object_creation_02::Which Java construct is most directly tied to object creation? {
=Constructors, factory methods, and builders are common object-creation techniques.
~Setter methods and mutating collection operations are common modification mechanisms.
~new is required for most class instantiation in Java.
~The == operator checks identity for object references.
}

::object_creation_03::Which example best demonstrates object creation in Java code? {
~int count = 0; is valid Java variable syntax.
~Calling Math.max(a, b) is a simple function-call example.
~new ArrayList<>() creates a new list object.
=A static factory like LocalDate.of(...) is an object creation example.
}

::object_creation_04::Which is a common mistake when working with object creation? {
~A common mistake is memorizing syntax without understanding object semantics.
~A common mistake is relying on side effects without clear execution order.
~A common mistake is duplicating initialization logic instead of chaining with this(...).
=A common mistake is exposing many telescoping constructors instead of clearer factories.
}

::object_creation_05::Which test most directly validates object creation behavior? {
~A strong proficiency test includes coding tasks plus reasoning about tradeoffs.
~A good test checks state transitions after each critical step.
~A good test checks both field initialization and invariants across related fields.
=Object-creation tests should confirm valid defaults and invariant setup.
}

::object_creation_06::Which performance/maintainability statement about object creation is most accurate? {
~Choosing mutable vs immutable types affects semantic clarity.
=Creation strategy can affect readability and memory behavior.
~Strong typing catches many errors before runtime.
~Command objects can reduce coupling between invoker code and business logic classes.
}

::object_creation_07::Which refactoring most improves code related to object creation? {
~Refactoring complex sequences into named methods improves traceability.
~Refactoring to generics improves type safety and reduces casts.
=Refactoring to a builder improves creation of objects with many optional fields.
~Refactoring to object pools is rare and only justified for measured hotspots.
}

::object_creation_08::Which Java API/keyword detail is most relevant to object creation? {
~The compiler performs static type checking on Java code.
~Java collections like Map<String, Command> are commonly used to dispatch commands.
=Dependency injection frameworks centralize object creation in larger systems.
~equals() and hashCode() define value semantics for custom classes.
}

::object_creation_09::Which debugging approach is most useful for object creation problems? {
~Breakpoints on call sites and callee methods are effective for tracing behavior.
=Creation bugs often surface as null fields or partially initialized objects.
~Debugging with this in watch expressions helps inspect current object state.
~Method-definition issues are easier to debug with clear parameter names and contracts.
}

::object_creation_10::Which statement about object creation is true? {
~Readable sequencing reduces accidental order-dependent bugs.
~Clear method names make call sites self-documenting.
~Constructors should establish valid invariants before methods are called.
=Good object creation APIs make invalid states hard to construct.
}
